  "output": "This session is scoped to `apps/crawler`, which is a pure Python news-crawler (no React/frontend code) — I'll note that and focus the analysis on what's actually here: state persistence, I/O, and per-article processing in `base.py` and `providers.py`.\n\n## Summary\n\n`apps/crawler` is a Python scraper (11 news providers) with no frontend/React code, so \"React re-renders\" doesn't apply here. The real hotspots are in the **resumable-crawl state machine** in `base.py:273-335`, which has an I/O-amplification pattern that's the closest analogue to an N+1 problem in this codebase.\n\n### 1. Biggest issue: O(n log n) full-state rewrite on every single article (base.py:308-314)\n\n```python\nseen.add(url)\nsaved.append(article)\nself._append_article(article)\nstate[\"seen_urls\"] = sorted(seen)          # ← re-sorts the ENTIRE seen set, every article\nstate[\"total_saved\"] = state.get(\"total_saved\", 0) + 1\nstate[\"last_run_at\"] = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()\nself._save_state(state)                     # ← re-serializes + rewrites the WHOLE file\n```\n\n`seen_urls` already has 1000+ entries for several providers (kolo-tv: 1605, malagasynews-mbs: 1205, lexpress-mg: 1359 — checked via `wc -l state/*.json`). This loop re-sorts and re-writes the **entire accumulated history** after every new article, not just the delta. For a 10-article run against a 1600-entry backlog, that's 10× (sort 1600 items + serialize + `Path.write_text` + `Path.replace`) — work that scales with total history, not with new work.\n\nFix — keep `seen` as a set in memory, only sort/serialize once per `crawl()` call (or every N articles), since crash-resumability only needs *a* recent checkpoint, not literally every article:\n\n```python\ndef crawl(self, limit=10, on_save=None) -> list[Article]:\n    state = self._load_state()\n    seen: set[str] = set(state.get(\"seen_urls\", []))\n    ...\n    for url in self.list_article_urls():\n        ...\n        seen.add(url)\n        self._append_article(article)   # still per-article — this one's cheap (append-only)\n        saved_count += 1\n        if saved_count % 5 == 0:        # checkpoint state every N articles instead of every 1\n            state[\"seen_urls\"] = sorted(seen)\n            self._save_state(state)\n        ...\n    state[\"seen_urls\"] = sorted(seen)   # final checkpoint always happens\n    self._save_state(state)\n```\n\nIf sort order doesn't matter for correctness (it's a lookup set, `sorted()` is presumably just for diff-friendliness), an even cheaper fix is dropping the sort entirely and storing `list(seen)`.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation: `get_all_text()` called twice per paragraph (base.py:183-187)\n\n```python\nbody = \"\\n\\n\".join(\n    p.get_all_text(strip=True)\n    for p in page.css(s.body)\n    if p.get_all_text(strip=True)   # ← recomputes the same extraction just to check truthiness\n)\n```\n\n`get_all_text(strip=True)` walks the DOM subtree and concatenates text nodes — doing it twice per `<p>` doubles that work for every article, across every provider. Fix:\n\n```python\ntexts = (p.get_all_text(strip=True) for p in page.css(s.body))\nbody = \"\\n\\n\".join(t for t in texts if t)\n```\n\n### 3. Caching opportunity: Moov fetches every article page twice (providers.py:224-236)\n\nAlready flagged in the code's own comment (\"each page is fetched twice — once here to expand the frontier, once in `parse_article`\"), but it's a real double network round-trip per article for this provider:\n\n```python\nwhile queue:\n    url = queue.popleft()\n    yield url\n    page = Fetcher.get(url, ...)   # fetched here for frontier expansion...\n    for link in page.css(\"a[href*='/article/']\"):\n        enqueue(...)\n# ...then parse_article() in base.py calls self.fetch(url) again for the same url\n```\n\nFix: cache the already-fetched `page` object (e.g. `functools.lru_cache` keyed by URL, or a small dict on `self`) and have `parse_article` check it before calling `self.fetch(url)` again. Comment even notes this ceiling is \"acceptable for a small site\" — worth revisiting if Moov's article count grows.\n\n### 4. Memory: unbounded `saved: list[Article]` for `--limit 0` runs (base.py:284, 309)\n\n```python\nsaved: list[Article] = []\n...\nsaved.append(article)   # full Article incl. body text + image URL list, held for entire run\n```\n\nEach `Article` already gets durably persisted via `_append_article` immediately, but the full object (body text, image list) is *also* retained in `saved` for the whole run just to return `len(articles)`/count at the end in `main.py:25`. For `--limit 0` (unlimited, run until exhausted — explicitly supported per the docstring) against a large provider like Midi (~118 sitemap sub-files), this list could grow to thousands of full article bodies resident in memory. Fix: track a counter instead, and only build a list if a caller actually needs the article objects back (currently `main.py` only uses the count and already gets live per-article data via `on_save`).\n\n### 5. Minor: per-article log file open (base.py:151-155)\n\n```python\ndef _log(self, message: str) -> None:\n    self._log_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n    with self._log_path.open(\"a\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:\n        f.write(...)\n```\n\nOpens/closes the log file on every call (mkdir syscall included). Low-impact at current volumes, but if throughput increases, hold the file handle open for the duration of `crawl()` instead.\n\n---\n\n**Not applicable here:** N+1 DB queries and React re-renders — there's no database or frontend code in `apps/crawler`. If you want the React/N+1-DB angle covered too, point me at the app that has it (the repo's recent commits mention a TanStack frontend) and I'll run the same analysis there.\n",
